---
import CalcolatoreLayout from '../../layouts/CalcolatoreLayout.astro';
import ConfrontoDipendentePIVA from '../../components/calcolatori/ConfrontoDipendentePIVA';
import { SITE } from '../../config';
import { canonicalURL } from '../../lib/seo';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = "Employee vs Freelancer Italy 2026: Net Income Compared";
const description = "Compare take-home pay as employee (dipendente) vs freelancer (P.IVA forfettario) in Italy. Side-by-side IRPEF, INPS, TFR, and total tax burden comparison.";
const canonical = canonicalURL('/en/employee-vs-freelancer/');

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: `${SITE.url}/en/` },
  { name: 'Calculators', url: `${SITE.url}/en/` },
  { name: 'Employee vs Freelancer', url: canonical },
];

const faqs = [
  { question: 'Is it better to be an employee or a freelancer (Partita IVA) in Italy?', answer: 'There is no universal answer. From a strictly fiscal perspective, the Partita IVA under the regime forfettario (flat-rate regime) can be more tax-efficient at low-to-medium revenue levels thanks to the reduced substitute tax. However, employees benefit from TFR severance, the 13th-month salary, paid holidays, sick pay, maternity/paternity leave, and employer pension contributions. For a fair comparison, your freelance revenue should be at least 30&ndash;50% higher than the equivalent employee RAL. The choice also depends on non-monetary factors such as flexibility, financial security, and personal risk tolerance.' },
  { question: 'How much do I need to invoice as a freelancer to earn the same as an employee?', answer: 'As a general rule, to achieve a net income equivalent to that of an employee (including TFR and the value of employment protections), your Partita IVA revenue should be roughly 30&ndash;50% higher than the employee RAL. For example, to match a RAL of &euro;40,000 you would need to bill approximately &euro;55,000&ndash;60,000 as a consultant under the regime forfettario. Use the calculator above for a precise estimate based on your specific profitability coefficient (coefficiente di redditivit&agrave;).' },
  { question: 'What happens if my freelance revenue exceeds &euro;85,000?', answer: 'If your revenues exceed &euro;85,000 but remain below &euro;100,000, you exit the regime forfettario starting from the following calendar year and transition to the regime ordinario (standard tax regime) with progressive IRPEF, VAT obligations, and full double-entry bookkeeping. If you exceed &euro;100,000, the exit is immediate &mdash; effective in the current year. Under the regime ordinario, the tax burden is significantly higher: progressive IRPEF (up to 43%), regional and municipal surcharges, and VAT to charge and remit.' },
  { question: 'Does a freelancer under the regime forfettario really pay less tax than an employee?', answer: 'In terms of the marginal tax rate, yes: the substitute tax of 5&ndash;15% is much lower than the progressive IRPEF which reaches 43%. However, the comparison is not straightforward. The forfettario freelancer pays 26.07% in INPS contributions on taxable income (compared to 9.19% for the employee, with the employer adding another 23.81%). Moreover, the forfettario cannot claim tax deductions for medical costs, mortgage interest, home renovations, or other standard reliefs. When you consider all factors &mdash; taxes, contributions, lost deductions, and the absence of employment protections &mdash; the real difference is much smaller than the headline rates suggest.' },
  { question: 'Can I be employed and have a Partita IVA at the same time?', answer: 'Yes, it is possible to be employed and simultaneously hold a Partita IVA, provided there is no exclusivity clause in your employment contract and no conflict of interest with your employer. From a tax perspective, you can still access the regime forfettario as an employee, on the condition that your employment income does not exceed &euro;30,000 gross per year (this is an additional requirement for those who also have an employment relationship). If your employee income exceeds this threshold, the regime forfettario is not available and your Partita IVA must operate under the standard regime ordinario.' },
  { question: 'How does the pension work for a freelancer in the INPS gestione separata?', answer: 'Holders of a Partita IVA enrolled in the INPS gestione separata (separate management fund) contribute 26.07% of their taxable income towards their pension. These contributions accumulate in a notional contribution pot (montante contributivo) and determine the future pension amount, calculated under Italy\'s contribution-based system (sistema contributivo). Because the forfettario taxable income is reduced by the profitability coefficient, the contributions actually paid &mdash; and therefore the future pension &mdash; will generally be lower than those of an employee with an equivalent RAL, whose employer pays an additional 23.81% on top. For this reason, many freelancers choose to supplement their state pension with private pension plans (fondi pensione aperti or piani individuali pensionistici).' },
  { question: 'Does a freelancer in the regime forfettario need to charge VAT?', answer: 'No. Freelancers operating under the regime forfettario issue invoices without VAT, pursuant to Art. 1, paragraph 58, of Law 190/2014. The invoice must include a specific exemption statement (dicitura di esenzione). This greatly simplifies accounting, but it has a flip side: the forfettario cannot deduct VAT on purchases. For private clients (B2C) this is an advantage because your prices are more competitive; for business clients (B2B) the effect is neutral because those clients cannot reclaim the input VAT on invoices received from a forfettario supplier.' },
  { question: 'I am an expat moving to Italy &mdash; should I start as an employee or open a Partita IVA?', answer: 'For most expats arriving in Italy, starting as an employee is generally the simpler and safer path. Employment provides a steady income, immediate access to the Italian healthcare system (SSN), a straightforward residency process, and familiarity with the tax system through your employer\'s payroll. Opening a Partita IVA requires choosing the right codice ATECO, registering with INPS, hiring a commercialista, and managing quarterly tax obligations &mdash; all in a foreign language and legal system. If you are considering freelancing, it is worth exploring the regime impatriati (expat tax incentive), which can reduce your taxable income by 50&ndash;70% for qualifying new residents. Use our Impatriati calculator to estimate potential savings.' },
  { question: 'What is the 5% reduced tax rate and who qualifies?', answer: 'New Partita IVA holders who meet certain requirements can pay a reduced substitute tax of just 5% for the first 5 years of activity, instead of the standard 15%. To qualify, you must not have held a Partita IVA in the same sector in the three years prior to opening, you must not be continuing a previously existing business activity (unless it was an apprenticeship or training period), and your annual revenues must remain below &euro;85,000. This reduced rate applies automatically if the conditions are met at the time of opening your Partita IVA. After 5 years, the rate increases to 15%.' },
];
---

<CalcolatoreLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  calculatorName="Employee vs Freelancer Calculator"
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  canonical={canonical}
  lang={lang}

  faqs={faqs}
>
  <ConfrontoDipendentePIVA client:load lang={lang} />

  <Fragment slot="come-si-calcola">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-6">
      When is freelancing better than employment in Italy &mdash; and when is it not?
    </h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        Choosing between <strong>permanent employment</strong> (<em>lavoro dipendente</em>) and
        <strong>freelancing with a Partita IVA</strong> (VAT number / freelancer registration) is one
        of the most consequential financial decisions you will face while working in Italy. There is no
        universal answer: the right choice depends on your income level, your professional sector, your
        risk tolerance, and personal factors such as the need for stability versus the desire for
        flexibility. This calculator helps you compare the real numbers side by side, but the final
        decision must also account for non-monetary benefits that are difficult to quantify.
      </p>
      <p>
        From a purely fiscal standpoint, the <strong>regime forfettario</strong> (flat-rate tax regime)
        for freelancers tends to be more tax-efficient at low-to-medium revenue levels (up to roughly
        &euro;50,000&ndash;60,000 in annual billings), thanks to the reduced substitute tax of 5% for
        the first five years and 15% thereafter, plus the absence of progressive IRPEF brackets.
        However, Italian employees enjoy a suite of protections and supplementary compensation
        components that carry real economic value &mdash; and these must be factored into any honest
        comparison.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-4">
        The hidden value of Italian employment (lavoro dipendente)
      </h3>
      <p>
        When comparing an employee's net salary with a freelancer's take-home pay, it is a common
        mistake to look only at the monthly net figure on the payslip (<em>busta paga</em>). The total
        compensation package of an Italian employee includes several additional components with tangible
        economic value:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>TFR (Trattamento di Fine Rapporto &mdash; severance pay)</strong>: equal to roughly
          6.91% of the gross annual salary or RAL (calculated as RAL&nbsp;/&nbsp;13.5). The employer
          sets aside this amount each year, and it is paid out when the employment relationship ends.
          For a RAL of &euro;40,000, this amounts to approximately &euro;2,963 per year. Freelancers
          have no equivalent benefit and must save independently for their own financial safety net.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Tredicesima (13th-month salary)</strong>: already included in the RAL, this
          represents an extra monthly payment that freelancers simply do not receive. A RAL of
          &euro;40,000 is spread across 13 monthly payments (approximately &euro;3,077 gross each),
          not 12.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Paid holidays (ferie retribuite)</strong>: Italian employees are entitled to at least
          26 working days of paid leave per year (four weeks minimum by law, plus public holidays and
          additional leave under the applicable CCNL &mdash; the national collective labour agreement).
          This is equivalent to roughly 10% of annual working time that is paid without working. A
          freelancer who does not work does not bill.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Paid sick leave (malattia retribuita)</strong>: when an employee falls ill, they
          continue to receive their salary (under the terms of their CCNL and INPS rules). A
          freelancer who is sick simply earns nothing. The INPS <em>gestione separata</em> (separate
          management fund) provides a sickness allowance, but only in the case of hospitalisation
          and at very limited amounts.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Maternity and paternity leave</strong>: female employees are entitled to 5 months of
          mandatory maternity leave paid at 80% of salary (with many CCNLs topping this up to 100%),
          plus optional parental leave. Male employees are entitled to 10 days of mandatory paternity
          leave paid at 100%. For holders of a Partita IVA enrolled in the INPS <em>gestione
          separata</em>, a maternity allowance exists but is calculated on a conventional basis and
          is usually lower than what employees receive.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>INAIL coverage (workplace injury insurance)</strong>: the employer pays INAIL
          contributions covering workplace accidents and occupational diseases. This cost is borne
          entirely by the company. A freelancer must arrange and pay for private insurance if they
          want similar protection.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Employer pension contributions (contributi previdenziali del datore)</strong>: the
          employer pays approximately 23.81% of the RAL in INPS pension contributions on top of the
          employee's salary. These contributions translate into a higher future pension for the
          employee. A freelancer enrolled in the <em>gestione separata</em> pays 26.07% of taxable
          income &mdash; which is already reduced by the profitability coefficient (<em>coefficiente
          di redditivit&agrave;</em>), resulting in lower lifetime pension accrual.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-4">
        The regime forfettario (flat-rate tax regime): advantages and limitations
      </h3>
      <p>
        The <strong>regime forfettario</strong> is Italy's simplified tax regime for freelancers and
        sole proprietors with annual revenues up to <strong>&euro;85,000</strong>. Its key advantages
        are:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Reduced substitute tax (imposta sostitutiva)</strong>: 5% for the first 5 years of
          activity (subject to specific eligibility criteria), rising to 15% thereafter. This single
          tax replaces IRPEF, regional and municipal surcharges, and IRAP.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Simplified bookkeeping</strong>: no obligation to charge VAT on invoices (invoices
          are VAT-exempt under Art. 1, para. 58, Law 190/2014), no VAT registers required, and no
          periodic VAT settlement filings.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No withholding tax (ritenuta d'acconto)</strong> applied on invoices issued.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        However, the <strong>limitations</strong> of the regime forfettario are equally important to
        understand:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>No deduction of actual expenses</strong>: business expenses are determined on a
          lump-sum basis using the profitability coefficient (<em>coefficiente di
          redditivit&agrave;</em>). If your real expenses exceed the flat-rate percentage, the regime
          becomes financially disadvantageous.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Revenue cap of &euro;85,000</strong>: once you exceed this threshold, you exit the
          regime (from the following year if you stay below &euro;100,000, or immediately if you
          exceed &euro;100,000).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>INPS gestione separata at 26.07%</strong>: the social security contribution rate is
          substantial and applies to the taxable income (not to total revenue). For those registered
          with professional pension funds (<em>casse previdenziali</em> such as INARCASSA for
          engineers or Cassa Forense for lawyers), the rates may differ.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No IRPEF deductions or credits</strong>: under the regime forfettario, you cannot
          claim tax deductions for medical expenses, mortgage interest, home renovations, energy
          efficiency bonuses, or other standard personal deductions. This can be a significant
          drawback for anyone with substantial deductible expenses.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-4">
        The comparison trap: RAL &euro;40,000 vs revenue &euro;40,000
      </h3>
      <p>
        One of the most common mistakes is to compare a RAL (<em>Retribuzione Annua Lorda</em> &mdash;
        gross annual salary) of &euro;40,000 with freelance revenue of &euro;40,000 as though they were
        equivalent. <strong>They are not.</strong> The employee's RAL already includes the 13th-month
        salary (it is split across 13 payments), and on top of the RAL the employee also receives TFR,
        paid holidays, sick leave, and the employer's pension contributions. The <strong>total employer
        cost</strong> (<em>costo azienda</em>) for an employee with a RAL of &euro;40,000 is
        approximately <strong>&euro;52,000&ndash;54,000</strong> (RAL + employer INPS contributions +
        TFR + INAIL).
      </p>
      <p>
        This means that for a fair like-for-like comparison, a freelancer would need to bill at least
        <strong>&euro;52,000&ndash;55,000</strong> to achieve a total compensation package equivalent
        to that of an employee with a RAL of &euro;40,000. And even then, the freelancer would not
        have protections in case of illness, maternity, or termination.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-4">
        Comparison table: employee RAL vs equivalent freelance revenue
      </h3>
    </div>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto mt-4">
      <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
        <thead class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
          <tr>
            <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Employee RAL</th>
            <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Employee net/year</th>
            <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Equiv. P.IVA revenue</th>
            <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">P.IVA net/year</th>
            <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200 dark:divide-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
          <tr>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">&euro;25,000</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;20,500</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;33,000</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;24,600</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-500 text-xs">Coeff. 78%, tax rate 15%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">&euro;30,000</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;23,800</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;40,000</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;29,200</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-500 text-xs">Coeff. 78%, tax rate 15%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">&euro;40,000</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;30,200</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;55,000</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;39,400</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-500 text-xs">Coeff. 78%, tax rate 15%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">&euro;50,000</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;36,100</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;68,000</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;48,700</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-500 text-xs">Coeff. 78%, tax rate 15%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">&euro;60,000</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;41,500</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;82,000</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~&euro;58,700</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-500 text-xs">Coeff. 78%, tax rate 15%</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none mt-6">
      <p>
        The table above shows that to achieve the same annual net income as an employee, a freelancer
        must bill significantly more. For example, to match an employee earning a RAL of &euro;40,000,
        an IT consultant operating under the regime forfettario (with a 78% profitability coefficient)
        would need to invoice approximately &euro;55,000. And this calculation does not even account
        for the economic value of the employee's additional protections (TFR severance, paid leave,
        sick pay, maternity and paternity rights).
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-4">
        Worked example: RAL &euro;40,000 vs freelance revenue &euro;55,000
      </h3>
      <p>
        Let us take an <strong>IT consultant</strong> who must choose between an employment offer at
        &euro;40,000 RAL and continuing as a freelancer billing &euro;55,000 per year.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>As an employee (RAL &euro;40,000)</strong>:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Employee INPS contributions (9.19%): ~&euro;3,676</li>
        <li>Net IRPEF (after deductions and tax wedge relief): ~&euro;6,100</li>
        <li>Regional and municipal surcharges: ~&euro;600</li>
        <li><strong>Annual net pay: ~&euro;30,200</strong> (~&euro;2,323/month across 13 payments)</li>
        <li>TFR accrued: ~&euro;2,963/year</li>
        <li>Employer INPS contributions: ~&euro;9,524</li>
        <li>Total employer cost: ~&euro;52,500</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <strong>As a freelancer in regime forfettario (revenue &euro;55,000, coeff. 78%)</strong>:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Taxable income (78% of revenue): &euro;42,900</li>
        <li>INPS gestione separata contributions (26.07%): ~&euro;11,184</li>
        <li>Tax base for substitute tax: &euro;31,716</li>
        <li>Substitute tax (imposta sostitutiva at 15%): ~&euro;4,757</li>
        <li><strong>Annual net income: ~&euro;39,059</strong> (~&euro;3,255/month across 12 payments)</li>
        <li>TFR accrued: &euro;0</li>
        <li>Paid holidays: 0 days</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        At first glance, the freelancer earns more (&euro;39,059 vs &euro;30,200). But once you add
        the employee's annual TFR (~&euro;2,963) and the economic value of 26 days of paid holiday
        (~&euro;4,000), the gap narrows significantly. Furthermore, the freelancer must cover
        professional expenses out of pocket &mdash; accountant fees (<em>commercialista</em>),
        software subscriptions, coworking spaces, professional insurance &mdash; none of which are
        deductible under the regime forfettario. When all these factors are taken into account, the
        two compensation packages become much closer than a simple net-to-net comparison would
        suggest.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-4">
        Non-monetary factors to consider
      </h3>
      <p>
        Beyond the numbers, the choice between employment and freelancing involves important
        qualitative factors that every expat in Italy should weigh carefully:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Flexibility</strong>: freelancers generally have more control over their schedule
          and choice of projects. They can work remotely, choose their clients, and organise their
          time as they see fit. Employees tend to have more rigid schedules but also benefit from a
          structure that many find reassuring.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Financial security</strong>: employees receive a guaranteed fixed salary, have
          protections in case of termination (notice period and NASpI unemployment benefit), paid
          sick leave, and predictable pension contributions. Freelancers are exposed to the risk of
          losing clients, late payments, and dry spells without assignments.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Career growth</strong>: within a company, employees can grow through promotions,
          pay rises, and employer-funded training. As a freelancer, career progression depends
          entirely on your ability to win new clients and develop new skills. On the other hand,
          freelancers can diversify their experience by working with multiple companies
          simultaneously.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Access to credit</strong>: obtaining a mortgage (<em>mutuo</em>) or a personal loan
          is generally much easier for an employee with a permanent contract (<em>contratto a tempo
          indeterminato</em>). Holders of a Partita IVA typically need to show at least 2&ndash;3
          years of stable revenues, and the terms offered by Italian banks are often less
          favourable.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Administrative burden</strong>: freelancers must manage their own invoicing,
          bookkeeping, tax filings, and interactions with INPS and the Agenzia delle Entrate
          (revenue agency). Even under the simplified regime forfettario, the annual cost of an
          accountant (<em>commercialista</em>) ranges from roughly &euro;600 to &euro;1,500.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Residency and immigration considerations</strong>: for non-EU expats, employment
          with an Italian company often provides a simpler path to residency permits. Opening a
          Partita IVA as a non-EU citizen requires a specific self-employment visa and additional
          bureaucratic steps. EU citizens can freely choose either route but should still consider
          how each status interacts with local residency registration (<em>residenza</em>).
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="valori">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-6">
      Tax and contribution parameters for {SITE.annoFiscale}
    </h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        The comparison between employment (lavoro dipendente) and freelancing under the regime
        forfettario is based on the following fiscal and social security parameters in force for the
        {SITE.annoFiscale} tax year:
      </p>
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">
        Employment (lavoro dipendente)
      </h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Employee INPS contributions: <strong>9.19%</strong> of RAL</li>
        <li>IRPEF brackets: 23% up to &euro;28,000 &bull; 35% from &euro;28,001 to &euro;50,000 &bull; 43% above &euro;50,000</li>
        <li>Employment tax deductions (<em>detrazioni lavoro dipendente</em>): up to &euro;1,955 per year</li>
        <li>Tax wedge relief (<em>cuneo fiscale</em>): contribution reduction / deduction for incomes up to &euro;40,000</li>
        <li>TFR severance accrual: approximately 6.91% of RAL (RAL&nbsp;/&nbsp;13.5)</li>
        <li>Employer INPS contributions: approximately 23.81% of RAL</li>
      </ul>
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">
        Freelancing under the regime forfettario (flat-rate regime)
      </h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Revenue cap: <strong>&euro;85,000</strong> per year</li>
        <li>Substitute tax (<em>imposta sostitutiva</em>): <strong>5%</strong> for the first 5 years, <strong>15%</strong> thereafter</li>
        <li>INPS gestione separata contributions: <strong>26.07%</strong> of taxable income</li>
        <li>Taxable income: revenue &times; profitability coefficient (<em>coefficiente di redditivit&agrave;</em>), which varies by ATECO sector code</li>
        <li>Tax base for substitute tax: taxable income &minus; INPS contributions</li>
        <li>No IRPEF deductions available, no regional or municipal surcharges</li>
      </ul>
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">
        Profitability coefficients by sector
      </h3>
      <p>
        The most common profitability coefficients (<em>coefficienti di redditivit&agrave;</em>) for
        workers in the services and technology sectors are: <strong>86%</strong> for IT and technical
        consulting, <strong>78%</strong> for intellectual professions (consulting, freelance
        professionals), and <strong>67%</strong> for general service activities. For retail trade and
        food services, the coefficients drop to <strong>40%</strong>, reflecting higher operating
        costs. The coefficient determines what percentage of your gross revenue is considered taxable
        income &mdash; a lower coefficient means a larger portion of revenue is treated as expenses.
      </p>
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-6 mb-4">
        Key Italian tax terms for expats
      </h3>
      <p>
        If you are new to the Italian tax system, here are the key terms you will encounter:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>RAL</strong> (<em>Retribuzione Annua Lorda</em>): gross annual salary, the standard benchmark for employment offers in Italy</li>
        <li><strong>IRPEF</strong> (<em>Imposta sul Reddito delle Persone Fisiche</em>): personal income tax, applied in progressive brackets</li>
        <li><strong>INPS</strong> (<em>Istituto Nazionale della Previdenza Sociale</em>): the national social security institute managing pensions and benefits</li>
        <li><strong>TFR</strong> (<em>Trattamento di Fine Rapporto</em>): mandatory severance pay accrued during employment</li>
        <li><strong>CCNL</strong> (<em>Contratto Collettivo Nazionale di Lavoro</em>): national collective labour agreement, which sets minimum pay, working hours, leave, and other conditions by sector</li>
        <li><strong>Commercialista</strong>: a chartered accountant / tax advisor, essential for anyone operating with a Partita IVA</li>
        <li><strong>Gestione separata</strong>: the INPS fund for freelancers and independent workers without a dedicated professional pension fund</li>
        <li><strong>Codice ATECO</strong>: the activity classification code assigned when you open a Partita IVA, which determines your profitability coefficient</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="faq">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-6">
      Frequently asked questions: employee vs freelancer in Italy
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Is it better to be an employee or a freelancer (Partita IVA) in Italy?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          There is no universal answer. From a strictly fiscal perspective, the Partita IVA under the
          regime forfettario (flat-rate regime) can be more tax-efficient at low-to-medium revenue
          levels thanks to the reduced substitute tax. However, employees benefit from TFR severance,
          the 13th-month salary, paid holidays, sick pay, maternity/paternity leave, and employer
          pension contributions. For a fair comparison, your freelance revenue should be at least
          30&ndash;50% higher than the equivalent employee RAL. The choice also depends on
          non-monetary factors such as flexibility, financial security, and personal risk tolerance.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          How much do I need to invoice as a freelancer to earn the same as an employee?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          As a general rule, to achieve a net income equivalent to that of an employee (including TFR
          and the value of employment protections), your Partita IVA revenue should be roughly
          30&ndash;50% higher than the employee RAL. For example, to match a RAL of &euro;40,000 you
          would need to bill approximately &euro;55,000&ndash;60,000 as a consultant under the regime
          forfettario. Use the calculator above for a precise estimate based on your specific
          profitability coefficient (<em>coefficiente di redditivit&agrave;</em>).
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What happens if my freelance revenue exceeds &euro;85,000?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          If your revenues exceed &euro;85,000 but remain below &euro;100,000, you exit the regime
          forfettario starting from the following calendar year and transition to the <em>regime
          ordinario</em> (standard tax regime) with progressive IRPEF, VAT obligations, and full
          double-entry bookkeeping. If you exceed &euro;100,000, the exit is immediate &mdash;
          effective in the current year. Under the regime ordinario, the tax burden is significantly
          higher: progressive IRPEF (up to 43%), regional and municipal surcharges, and VAT to
          charge and remit.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Does a freelancer under the regime forfettario really pay less tax than an employee?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          In terms of the marginal tax rate, yes: the substitute tax of 5&ndash;15% is much lower
          than the progressive IRPEF which reaches 43%. However, the comparison is not
          straightforward. The forfettario freelancer pays 26.07% in INPS contributions on taxable
          income (compared to 9.19% for the employee, with the employer adding another 23.81%).
          Moreover, the forfettario cannot claim tax deductions for medical costs, mortgage interest,
          home renovations, or other standard reliefs. When you consider all factors &mdash; taxes,
          contributions, lost deductions, and the absence of employment protections &mdash; the real
          difference is much smaller than the headline rates suggest.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Can I be employed and have a Partita IVA at the same time?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          Yes, it is possible to be employed and simultaneously hold a Partita IVA, provided there is
          no exclusivity clause in your employment contract and no conflict of interest with your
          employer. From a tax perspective, you can still access the regime forfettario as an
          employee, on the condition that your employment income does not exceed &euro;30,000 gross
          per year (this is an additional requirement for those who also have an employment
          relationship). If your employee income exceeds this threshold, the regime forfettario is
          not available and your Partita IVA must operate under the standard regime ordinario.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          How does the pension work for a freelancer in the INPS gestione separata?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          Holders of a Partita IVA enrolled in the INPS gestione separata (separate management fund)
          contribute 26.07% of their taxable income towards their pension. These contributions
          accumulate in a notional contribution pot (<em>montante contributivo</em>) and determine
          the future pension amount, calculated under Italy's contribution-based system (<em>sistema
          contributivo</em>). Because the forfettario taxable income is reduced by the profitability
          coefficient, the contributions actually paid &mdash; and therefore the future pension &mdash;
          will generally be lower than those of an employee with an equivalent RAL, whose employer
          pays an additional 23.81% on top. For this reason, many freelancers choose to supplement
          their state pension with private pension plans (<em>fondi pensione aperti</em> or
          <em>piani individuali pensionistici</em>).
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Does a freelancer in the regime forfettario need to charge VAT?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          No. Freelancers operating under the regime forfettario issue invoices without VAT, pursuant
          to Art. 1, paragraph 58, of Law 190/2014. The invoice must include a specific exemption
          statement (<em>dicitura di esenzione</em>). This greatly simplifies accounting, but it has
          a flip side: the forfettario cannot deduct VAT on purchases. For private clients (B2C)
          this is an advantage because your prices are more competitive; for business clients (B2B)
          the effect is neutral because those clients cannot reclaim the input VAT on invoices
          received from a forfettario supplier.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          I am an expat moving to Italy &mdash; should I start as an employee or open a Partita IVA?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          For most expats arriving in Italy, starting as an employee is generally the simpler and
          safer path. Employment provides a steady income, immediate access to the Italian healthcare
          system (SSN), a straightforward residency process, and familiarity with the tax system
          through your employer's payroll. Opening a Partita IVA requires choosing the right codice
          ATECO, registering with INPS, hiring a commercialista, and managing quarterly tax
          obligations &mdash; all in a foreign language and legal system. If you are considering
          freelancing, it is worth exploring the <em>regime impatriati</em> (expat tax incentive),
          which can reduce your taxable income by 50&ndash;70% for qualifying new residents.
          Use our <a href="/en/impatriati-tax-regime/" class="text-brand hover:underline">Impatriati
          calculator</a> to estimate potential savings.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What is the 5% reduced tax rate and who qualifies?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          New Partita IVA holders who meet certain requirements can pay a reduced substitute tax of
          just 5% for the first 5 years of activity, instead of the standard 15%. To qualify, you
          must not have held a Partita IVA in the same sector in the three years prior to opening,
          you must not be continuing a previously existing business activity (unless it was an
          apprenticeship or training period), and your annual revenues must remain below &euro;85,000.
          This reduced rate applies automatically if the conditions are met at the time of opening
          your Partita IVA. After 5 years, the rate increases to 15%.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

